---

Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Remove the ends from the @Chantenay carrots{250%g} (no need to peel!) and halve lengthways (if there are any bigger carrots, cut them into quarters!). Pop the carrots on a #baking tray{}. Drizzle over a glug of oil and season with a good pinch of @salt{}. Sprinkle on two-thirds of the @poudre de colombo{1%tsp}, mix well, then roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway to make sure they cook evenly.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced) into half moons. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @coriander{10%g} (stalks and all). Heat a large #saucepan{} over medium heat and add a splash of oil. Add the shallot and a pinch of salt. Cook until soft, ~{3%minutes}, then add half the garlic and half the @cumin seeds{1%tsp}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more, then stir in the remaining poudre de colombo and the @red split lentils{150%g}.

Add the @water{400%ml}, bring to the boil, then stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1/2%cube}. Make sure it is dissolved, reduce the heat and simmer gently for around ~{20%minutes}.

> Tip: If the mixture starts to look a little dry, just add a splash more water.

Heat a #frying pan{} over medium heat and add the remaining cumin seeds. Cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the @olive oil{2%tbsp}. Stir in the rest of the garlic, cook for ~{2%minutes}, then pour the flavoured oil into a small #bowl{}.

Wipe your frying pan with some #kitchen paper{}, then pop it back on high heat. When the pan is hot, dry-fry the @super soft tortillas with whole wheat{4} for ~{30%seconds} on each side. You want the tortillas to char slightly, so keep an eye on them. Transfer each tortilla to a #plate{} making a chapati pile and drizzle some of the flavoured oil over each one as you go. Cover with some #foil{} to keep warm.

When the lentils are cooked, add the @baby spinach{125%g} to the pan and stir it through to wilt it. Check the seasoning and add more salt and @ground black pepper{} if needed. Spoon the dal into #bowls{} and top with the roasted carrots. Finish with a dollop of @Greek style natural yoghurt{100%g}, a sprinkling of coriander and serve with the chapatis on the side. Yum!